<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   BJP Leader: Country `Should Exercise' Nuclear Option </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    BJP Leader: Country `Should Exercise' Nuclear Option </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1006100794 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1006100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The BJP [Bharatiya Janata Party] president, Mr. L.K. 
Advani, says India should exercise the nuclear option for 
national security and to prevent any attempt of intimidation of 
neighbors and superpowers. Addressing the three-day national 
council meeting of the party in Wadodara this morning, he warned 
of dangers to the country arising out of, what he termed, the 
U.S. tilt toward Pakistan. Mr. Advani also alleged that the 
policies of the Narasimha Rao government will affect both the 
economic and security interest of the nation. The BJP president 
said behind the nonproliferation initiative of the United States 
is the assumption that India must subcontract its national 
security to Washington. He said western influences, particularly 
American interests, shape the debate on nuclear arms and missile 
system. Mr. Advani said his party is opposed to the 
globalization policies of the government. He called for a 
reversal of the priorities and said that foreign trade and 
investment should only be useful supplements to national effort. 
  More than 300 delegates are attending the national council 
session which began this morning. Prominent leaders attending 
the meeting include Mr. Atal Behari Vajpayee and Mr. Murli 
Manohar Joshi. 

</TEXT>

