<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Unable To Ban `Murderers' in Palestinian Police </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Unable To Ban `Murderers' in Palestinian Police </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1506183594 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1506183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Israel will not be able to prevent murderers of 
Jews from serving in the Palestinian police. This emerges from 
a letter sent by the Information Department of the Prime 
Minister's Office which was obtained by our political 
correspondent Gadi Sukenik. A resident of the settlement of 
Teqoa' in the territories wrote a letter to the prime minister 
asking whether the murderers of Jews, including the man who 
murdered his neighbor and was released, will be allowed to serve 
in the Palestinian police, or will Israel prevent this. 
  The letter of reply from the Prime Minister's Office says, 
among other things, that the Israeli Government will continue 
fighting terrorism and hunt down those sabotaging peace, but 
will not be able to determine who can serve in the Palestinian 
police. 

</TEXT>

