<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Said To Call For Settling Refugees in Lebanon </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Said To Call For Settling Refugees in Lebanon </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1506121594 Beirut AL-ANWAR in Arabic 9 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC1506121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut AL-ANWAR </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, AL-ANWAR--Arab diplomatic sources close to 
the Palestinian-U.S. meetings--Yasir 'Arafat's meetings with 
Robert Pelletreau, U.S. assistant secretary of state for Middle 
Eastern affairs, last month and with U.S. Ambassador to Tunisia 
John McCarthy the day before yesterday--disclosed that 'Arafat 
raised several issues with Pelletreau and again with Ambassador 
McCarthy. 
  Those issues include the slowdown in the receipt of funds 
necessary to run the self-rule mechanism and the fate of the 
Palestinian residents in Lebanon and Syria, since they are not 
allowed to return under the Gaza-Jericho agreement, which closes 
the door to the return of the refugees from 1948. Most 
Palestinians residing in Syria and Lebanon are refugees from 
1948. 
  According to close diplomatic sources, 'Arafat expressed a 
wish for the Palestinians in Lebanon to be granted citizenship 
and permanent resettlement there. 'Arafat said to Pelletreau: 
Do you have any other option? The U.S. official was silent 
before saying: "It is a proposal worthy of consideration." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

