<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hasan Affirms Support for `Comprehensive Peace' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hasan Affirms Support for `Comprehensive Peace' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1606184194 Amman Jordan Television Network in Arabic 1700 
GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1606184194 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] His Highness Crown Prince Hasan, the regent, has 
stressed that we are facing a new challenge in the peace 
process. In a speech he delivered at the Royal War College, his 
highness added that peace in the Middle East figures high on the 
international agenda. He said Jordan has always been a peace 
advocate, and that Jordan's peace theory is not just theoretical 
propaganda, but an essential practical reality. 
  In his the lecture, his highness reviewed the challenges 
facing the Arab nation under changing world circumstances. His 
highness said the world's interests have become intertwined. 
Therefore, small states have lost a great degree of their 
freedom, and their decisions are affected by the international 
axis more than by regional and domestic axes. He indicated that 
the continued Arab-Israeli conflict threatens cruel 
international disputes. 
  [Begin Hasan recording] We want a peace that preserves our 
historical and religious rights in the holy land and holy 
Jerusalem. Peace should not be a bargain of material profits at 
the expense of moral and spiritual sublimeness. Any peace that 
does not secure our rights cannot be a durable peace. For peace 
not to be fragile, we want peace for all Arab parties. Peace is 
indivisible. A just peace is a comprehensive peace on all 
fronts. We are not raising this as a slogan, but as a message 
that this is the only possible peace whose hopes and pains we 
can cope with. For us in Jordan, the requirements of peace are 
unchangeable. They will require us to face the burdens of peace 
with internal cohesion, comprehensive security, building a 
production base, and resolving the shortage in basic supplies, 
such as water, energy, and food. [end recording] 
  Present to listen to the lecture were Acting Prime Minister 
Dhuqan al-Hindawi, advisers to his majesty the king, the 
information minister, his highness the prince's special adviser, 
chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, the chief of staff of the 
Royal Ground Forces, aides to the chairman of the Joint Chiefs 
of Staff, and senior Armed Forces officers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

