<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy Outlines Steps To Resolve Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Envoy Outlines Steps To Resolve Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1606135494 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 16 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1606135494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Salih Qallab: "Brahimi Tells AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT: </F>
Three Steps To Resolve Yemeni Crisis; They Begin With 
Cease-Fire"] 
  [Text] Lakhdar Brahimi, envoy of the UN secretary general, 
has emphasized that the situation in Yemen is not easy. 
However, he said that both sides are aware that the situation 
is very serious and that the Yemenis could lose control of the 
situation if matters continue as they stand and if the war is 
not brought to an end quickly. 
  Brahimi told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT during his stopover in Amman 
that the reality of the past four years has created very 
difficult conditions, and that the failure of the attempts to 
secure a solution over these years has made matters more 
difficult. 
  The international envoy defined three phases for his current 
mission: 
  First, the two parties must be convinced that the fighting 
will lead to nothing but ruin and destruction, and that its 
continuation would cause the Yemenis to lose control of the 
situation. 
  Second, after everyone reaches this conviction, they must be 
convinced that the solution lies in dialogue and that reaching 
an understanding through dialogue is the only way to resolve the 
Yemeni crisis. 
  Third, if the first two steps are achieved and the two sides 
sit at the negotiating table, certainly every party is going to 
bring its conditions with it...and we will talk about it then. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

