<DOCNO> FBIS4-37143 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes117ee_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-117 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> OPEC Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iranian Nominee Comments on Oil Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iranian Nominee Comments on Oil Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606143094 Tehran IRNA in English 1345 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 16, IRNA -- Demands for oil across the 
world are expected to rise to 79 million barrels per day by the 
year 2010 from 65 million BPD at present, Iranian Ambassador to 
Japan Hosein Kazempur-Ardabili said Thursday [16 June]. 
  The member states of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries could meet more than 53 percent of the world's oil 
demands, he told IRNA. 
  The ambassador urged OPEC member states not to let political 
differences have adverse effect on their economic interests. 
  Kazempur, who has been nominated by Iran for the post of 
OPEC 
secretary general, said it would be regrettable to make any 
concession to buyers and let them buy this God-given gift at the 
lowest price just because of political differences. 
  He said the most important role that OPEC can play now was 
to 
prevent political differences among its members from having any 
adverse effects on their economic interests. 
  Kazempur felt confidence that by setting an oil output 
ceiling and taking into consideration the growing demands for 
oil, OPEC would soon witness considerable increase in the prices 
of oil provided that its members refrain from overproducing. 
  OPEC members are now meeting in Vienna to determine an oil 
production ceiling and elect OPEC's new secretary general. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

