<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th: Talks on Extending Autonomy Begin 27 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sha'th: Talks on Extending Autonomy Begin 27 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1906153294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1355 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1906153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Gaza, 19 Jun (MENA) -- Dr. Nabil Sha'th, head of the 
Palestinian delegation to the Palestinian-Israeli Liaison 
Committee, has announced that it has agreed in principle to 
begin negotiations on the establishment of autonomy over the 
remainder of the West Bank on Monday, 27 June. 
  After meeting for two hours today with Major General Amnon 
Shahaq, head of the Israeli delegation to the Liaison Committee, 
Sha'th said that they agreed to hold the meetings alternately in 
Gaza and Jerusalem. 
  Sha'th pointed out that the date of each of these meetings 
will be set after consultation with Maj. Gen. Shahaq. 
  Sha'th added that he and Shahaq also discussed problems 
connected to the application of autonomy such as travel permits 
for the Palestinians and resuming the talks about Palestinian 
detainees in Israeli jails. He explained that Israel has so far 
released only 1,200 detainees out of a total of 5,000 who should 
have been released in line with the agreement between the two 
sides. He said negotiations over the release of the others will 
be conducted during the next meeting with Shahaq. 
  Sha'th said he will meet in the near future with Israeli 
Police Affairs Minister Moshe Shahal to discuss the conditions 
of the detainees who have not yet been released. 
  The Palestinian official reported that Israel has approved 
the entry of the families of the Palestinian police, totaling 
50,000 people, and also approved the return of 72 other 
Palestinian families who until now have been residing in Rafah's 
Egyptian sector. They will move to the village of Tall 
al-Sultan in the Gaza Strip. 
  Amnon Shahaq announced that Dr. Sha'th does not intend to 
visit Jerusalem tomorrow because he will be occupied elsewhere. 
  Sha'th has asked that the number of Palestinian workers who 
work inside Israel be increased. Israel formerly suspended the 
work permits of approximately 130,000 workers, except 10,000 
workers from Gaza. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

