<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jerusalem Municipal Limits on Agenda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jerusalem Municipal Limits on Agenda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2006093094 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 20 Jun 94 p A1 </F>
<F P=103> TA2006093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben] </F>
  [Excerpts] [Passage omitted] In their discussions on the 
interim agreement for the West Bank, Israel and the PLO will 
discuss determining the municipal boundaries of Jerusalem, which 
will be outside the autonomy. Israel is demanding that the 
current municipal boundaries, determined in 1967, be maintained. 
In recent discussions in government forums, a proposal was made 
to ease the restrictions imposed on the entry of Palestinians 
from the West Bank into the city in return for a PLO agreement 
to make changes in the municipal boundaries in order to reduce 
friction between Jews and Arabs in Jerusalem. 
  In a previous discussion on Jerusalem, held on 26 May, Prime 
Minister Rabin decided to prevent the establishment of new 
Palestinian political bodies and ban their policing activity in 
the city. 
  The prime minister instructed the Israel Police and the Shin 
Bet to closely monitor Orient House, the seat of the Palestinian 
delegation in East Jerusalem, and to immediately put an end to 
any illegal activity uncovered there. Over the past several 
days, security elements have reported that the preventive 
activity undertaken by the police and the Shin Bet regarding 
Orient House has led the Palestinians to "lower their profile" 
and curbed illegal activity in the building. [passage omitted] 
  In recent discussions between Police Minister Moshe Shahal 
and Faysal al-Husayni, the minister proposed that the parties 
draft a joint list of Palestinian institutions operating in East 
Jerusalem to serve as a basis for maintaining the status quo in 
the city, as promised by Israel in Foreign Minister Shim'on 
Peres' letter of 11 October 1993. Israel promised to protect 
the functioning of all the Palestinian institutions in the city. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

