<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PFLP Organizes Antipeace Demonstrations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PFLP Organizes Antipeace Demonstrations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1706193094 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1706193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yoram Kohen] </F>
  [Excerpts] Mass demonstrations against the peace agreement 
were held today in the Gaza Strip and Jericho. The 
demonstrators also called for the release of all Palestinian 
prisoners. Violent clashes between Hebron residents and 
soldiers took place today against the background of the growing 
tension surrounding the prisoner release. Our correspondent 
Yoram Kohen reports: 
  What may have looked like just another demonstration for the 
release of all the Palestinian prisoners was actually more than 
that. Today's demonstrations in Jericho were really a protest 
against the peace process. This afternoon, over 2,000 
supporters of the rejectionist organizations, mostly from George 
Habash's Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine [PFLP], 
gathered to protest the Gaza-Jericho First agreement while 
demanding the immediate release of all Palestinian prisoners. 
The demonstration marched uninterrupted down the town's main 
streets. Palestinian policemen were prepared for the event but 
did not intervene. 
  Earlier, after Friday prayers, hundreds of Hamas [Islamic 
Resistance Movement] supporters demonstrated in the town for the 
same reasons. The Hamas activists, however, had a different 
slogan. They shouted that Islam is the solution. [passage 
omitted] 
  Residents of the Gaza Strip also demonstrated today over the 
prisoner issue. The demonstrations have been held every day for 
a week now. The rally was organized by the PFLP. The residents 
are furious with the Palestinian leadership and claim it 
capitulated to Israel on this issue. 
  Nabil Sha'th said today that the negotiations on the release 
of those prisoners who still remain in jail will start at the 
beginning of next week. Up till now, approximately 1,300 
prisoners have refused to sign a commitment to stop terrorist 
activity. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

