<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Salih, Defense Minister Said To Differ Over Entering Aden </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Salih, Defense Minister Said To Differ Over Entering Aden </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1906085694 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 19 Jun 94 p 24 </F>
<F P=103> JN1906085694 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Exclusive" report by Fathi al-Qatta' in Sanaa] </F>
  [Text] Early this week, the Yemeni Foreign Ministry 
stopped financial remittances through the Yemeni Central Bank to 
some of its diplomatic missions and embassies abroad. Those 
include the embassies in Washington, New Delhi, Rome, Havana, 
Cairo, Muscat, Tehran, and Nairobi. The measure was adopted 
because the majority of the staff of those embassies supports 
the secessionist step declared by 'Ali Salim al-Bid on 21 May. 
  Last week, Najib al-Haddi, a leader of the Yemeni Reform 
Grouping [YRG] and brother-in-law of Shaykh 'Abd-al-Majid 
al-Zindani, member of the Presidential Council, was killed in 
the battlefield. Muqbil al-Fil, a member of the Yemeni House of 
Representatives and a leader of the YRG, was also killed. 
  Official and semiofficial Yemeni newspapers, as well as some 
parties that support unity, have launched fierce media campaigns 
against Saudi Arabia after its involvement in the Yemeni crisis 
and support for the secessionists diplomatically and militarily. 
  During President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih's visit to the two 
newly created camps of Zafar and al-Fatah in Dhamar last week, 
it was noticed for the first time that there were tanks having a 
different color of soil and desert. It was learned that these 
tanks were sent by Saudi Arabia to the secessionist forces 
through the Sharurah region, under Saudi occupation, near 
Hadhramaut. The forces of legitimacy seized those tanks but did 
not announce this. 
  There have been some changes in the military leaders. Some 
commanders who are close to President Salih were dismissed. 
Those included Colonel Ahmad Faraj, commander of the Khalid 
Bin-al-Walid Camp, and Colonel 'Abdallah al-Qadi, commander of 
the Infantry Brigade. The two camps are in Ta'izz. The 
commanders were dismissed because of the losses sustained by the 
forces of the two camps on the fronts. 
  It is also rumored in Sanaa that there has been a recent 
dispute between President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih and Brigadier 
General 'Abd-Rabbuh Mansur Hadi, the defense minister, because 
the latter refused to storm Aden justifying this by the great 
losses that the forces will incur, as well as the civilian 
losses. Hadi thinks what should be done is only to tighten the 
siege around Aden for some time and consequently bring about a 
change within the leadership and the military command of the 
Yemeni Socialist Party. 
  Sanaa restored direct contacts with the outside world 
yesterday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-37240 </DOCNO>
