<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Asnaj To Urge New UN Move Over Continuing War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Asnaj To Urge New UN Move Over Continuing War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1706131694 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 17 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM1706131694 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Lutfi Shatarah: "Al-Asnaj Tells AL-SHARQ </F>
AL-AWSAT: Urgent Contacts With Ghali To Urge New International 
Move"] 
  [Text] London -- South Yemen Foreign Minister 'Abdallah 
al-Asnaj has stressed that the southern leadership is going to 
seek urgent contacts with UN Secretary General Dr. Butrus-Ghali 
over the latest military developments. 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT al-Asnaj said that the 
south will urge the UN secretary general to make a move in the 
framework of the UN Security Council resolution, which 
authorizes him to brief the Security Council on developments in 
the situation in Yemen and to discuss the means capable of 
deterring the regime from violating international legitimacy and 
putting it in its place as an enemy of humanity and peace in the 
regime. The southern foreign minister accused President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih of working to thwart the efforts being made by 
the UN secretary general and his special envoy to Yemen Lakhdar 
Ibrahimi to establish peace in Yemen. 
  He said that the continuation of the war declared by 
President Salih against the Yemeni people in the Democratic 
Republic of Yemen confirms his aggressive tendency and the 
untruthfulness of what he says, namely that he has accepted UN 
Security Council Resolution 924, which calls for an immediate 
cease-fire in Yemen. Al-Asnaj stressed that President's Salih 
forces, which are besieging Aden, have over the past two days 
shelled mosques, schools, and residential areas. And that they 
have fired more than seven rockets on the city, killing many 
children, women, and men in various parts of Lahij and Aden 
Governorates. 
  He also said that 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih is living under a big 
delusion, namely that he is still president of what used to be 
called the Republic of Yemen. He said that his attack on Aden 
and his haphazard bombardment of it have provoked feelings of 
anger in Arab, Islamic, and many other states. 
  The Yemeni minister, who is expected to arrive in Washington 
within the next 24 hours in the framework of southern diplomatic 
moves designed to rally political support for the new republic, 
added that the international community is tired of the northern 
leadership's attitudes after the confirmation of its 
noncompliance with the UN Security Council resolution, violation 
of the principles of the Islamic Shari'ah, and persistence in 
committing further war crimes. Al-Asnaj said that Sanaa's 
continuation of the war confirms its involvement in expansionist 
schemes of states outside Yemen designed to disrupt security and 
undermine stability in the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

