<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former President Denies Involvement in Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former President Denies Involvement in Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1806185694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1835 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1806185694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Damascus, 18 Jun (MENA) -- Former South Yemeni 
President 'Ali Nasir Muhammad has denied that his supporters in 
the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] or the General People's 
Congress are involved in the current tragic events in Yemen. 
  In statements he made to the MENA correspondent in Damascus, 
'Ali Nasir Muhammad stressed that his supporters are the victims 
of this bloody conflict between the sons of the Yemeni people. 
He said that he is very pained by the reports by press agencies 
and international and humanitarian organizations on the tragic 
situation in Aden. 
  President 'Ali Nasir was commenting on a recent newspaper 
report that former leaders from South Yemen are involved in the 
fighting against the YSP so as to rehabiliate themselves and 
avenge the incidents of January 1986 that led to his ousting 
from his position. 
  The former south Yemeni president held some parties in the 
Yemeni leadership, which he did not name, responsible for the 
political and military conflict in Yemen. 
  He stressed that there must be a return to dialogue and a 
cease-fire, that the Yemeni leaders have to abide by the spirit 
of the Pledge and Accord Document, and that they have to deal 
flexibly and realistically with the UN envoy's endeavors. 
  He reiterated that he will not assume any responsibility in 
Yemen while there is fighting or secession, adding that the 
problem is a political one, not a military one. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

