<HT>    "drnes118_h_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-118 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Tunisia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Communique Issued </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Joint Communique Issued </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706235394 Tunis Tunisian Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
2100 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706235394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tunis Tunisian Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Tunisian-Namibian joint statement was issued 
following the official visit to Tunisia by President Sam Nujoma 
of the Republic of Namibia starting 16 June at the invitation of 
President Zine Al-Abidine Ben Ali. The statement said: 
  On this occasion the two state presidents, in an amicable 
atmosphere, held a series of talks which allowed them to look 
into bilateral relations and means to strengthen them and to 
exchange views on current affairs on both the African and world 
arenas. They both expressed their satisfaction at the ideal 
ties that link their two brotherly countries and their strong 
commitment to African solidarity and human values and their firm 
determination to bolster democracy and human rights. [passage 
omitted] 
  The two leaders reviewed current affairs at the regional and 
international levels; they recorded with satisfaction their 
agreement over the various issues discussed. In this context, 
they reiterated their commitment to the principles and goals of 
the United Nations and the Organization of African Unity [OAU] 
and decided to intensify consultations between officials from 
the two countries during bilateral meetings and international 
and regional conferences. [passage omitted] 
  The two presidents stressed the importance of the 
resolutions 
issued by the OAU Tunisian summit and which are to bolster peace 
and cooperation in Africa and promote Africa's role on the world 
arena. 
  Regarding the situation in Africa, presidents Ben Ali and 
Nujoma expressed their satisfaction at the efforts made towards 
a peaceful settlement of all the conflicts in the continent in 
order to create a suitable atmosphere for peace, security, and 
development. They also expressed their satisfaction at the 
success of the democratic process in South Africa, an event 
which would give the African continent a positive impetus at the 
political and economic levels. The two presidents discussed the 
Rwandan crisis and expressed satisfaction at the indications of 
detente, manifested in the agreement of the two parties to halt 
hostilities, and expressed their wish that dialogue would help 
achieve national reconciliation in this African country. 
  Regarding the situation in the Middle East, the Namibian and 
Tunisian presidents hailed the brave struggle fought by the 
Palestinian people to establish its independent state on its 
land and expressed satisfaction at the positive and encouraging 
progress in the Middle East peace process according to UN 
resolutions. 

</TEXT>

