<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hekmatyar Spokesman Calls For Rabbani's Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hekmatyar Spokesman Calls For Rabbani's Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806154794 Tehran IRNA in English 1534 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1806154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad, June 18, IRNA -- A spokesman for 
Golboddin Hekmatyar's Hezb-e Eslami (Islamic Party) of 
Afghanistan Ghariburrahman Saeed [name as received] here 
Saturday [18 June] rejected Herat Governor Esmail Khan's 
proposal on Friday concerning convention of a session in Herat 
attended by Afghan party leaders. 
  Talking to IRNA in Peshawar Saturday Saeed said that 
convening of any seminar and participation in it would be 
"useless" and the sole way out of the current crisis is Afghan 
President Borhanoddin Rabbani's stepping down from power. 
  He called on Iran, Saudi Arabia and Pakistan to end the 
ongoing crisis in Afghanistan by forcing Rabbani to abide by 
Islamabad agreement and quit power. 
  Based on the agreement, signed by Afghan Mojahedin groups 
here on March 8, 1993 in presence of representatives of Iran, 
Pakistan and Saudi Arabia, Rabbani should abandon the 
presidential post by June 28 or would be compelled to do so by 
the said countries. 
  Esmail Khan along with governors of 15 other Afghan 
provinces 
had launched efforts from early last week to find a solution to 
put an end to the differences between Afghan Mojahedin groups. 
  He had in his proposal called on Afghan belligerent parties 
to participate in a conference in Herat to explore a peace 
formula. 

</TEXT>

