<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman on Possible Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman on Possible Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1906203894 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 1930 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1906203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A spokesman for Afghanistan's president announced in 
Kabul on Sunday [19 June] that Mr. Rabbani is neither thinking 
of continuing to work as the president, nor he is thinking of 
resigning. He is rather thinking that a legal authority would 
be found to take a decision on the future presidency of 
Afghanistan. The term of office of Borhaboddin Rabbani, as the 
president, and Golboddin Hekmatyar, as the prime minister, 
should end in less than 10 days' time, on the basis of decisions 
made by the Islamabad and Jalalabad meetings. 
  At the same time a member of the mediation team from the 
southwestern sector of Afghanistan, Dr. Shams, whose objective 
is to resolve the country's crisis through peaceful means, said 
today that this team has carried out the second round of its 
mediatory talks with Rabbani and Hekmatyar on Saturday and 
Sunday, and it has been agreed the two sides' representatives 
should begin direct talks from Monday. He expressed the hope 
that during the first round of talks between the representatives 
of Afghanistan's president and prime minister, the time of 
cease-fire and the time of opening the routes leading to Kabul 
would be determined and declared. 
  Dr. Shams said: Almost all the leaders of Afghanistan's 
jihad 
groups have announced that they will take part at the 
consultative and decision-taking session of Herat; and it is 
very much hoped that peace would be established in Afghanistan. 

</TEXT>

