<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Reviews U.S. Envoy Wells' Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Reviews U.S. Envoy Wells' Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA1706210694 Khartoum SUNA in Arabic 1600 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> EA1706210694 </F>
<F P=104>  Khartoum SUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Khartoum, 17 June (SUNA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton's envoy, Melissa Wells, will head for Washington to 
submit her report to the U.S. Administration on the talks she 
held with President Lieutenant General al-Bashir and the heads 
of the four Intergovernmental Authority on Drought and 
Development states, which concentrated on the issue of peace and 
humanitarian affairs. 
  The U.S. envoy left Sudan on 15 June for Nairobi to meet 
with 
rebel leaders, thereby completing her report, which will embrace 
the different viewpoints on the issues of relief and peace. 
  This was stated in Sudan by Mityang Malwal, the director of 
the peace department in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, 
speaking in today's edition of AL INQADH AL-WATANI. 
  He said the U.S. envoy's program included another mission on 
the issue of relief, which would take her to Geneva to hold 
talks with international donor agencies. His excellency the 
ambassador said that he accompanied the U.S. envoy to Kadugli in 
southern Kurdufan state, and to Wau in the western state of Bahr 
al-Ghazal, where they toured refugee camps and learned about 
different relief organizations' activities. His excellency said 
the situation was stable, and that relief work and services to 
refugees were continuing. 
  He said the envoy listened to a report from the Catholic 
archbishop in Wau, workers from the Islamic Call organization, 
and the Muwaffaq Charitable Organization, which he said 
confirmed that there was a great degree of peaceful coexistence 
between Muslims and Christians. 
  Mr. Mityang reiterated the government's commitment to the 
passage of relief supplies, agreements on humanitarian 
activities, and the provision of food to all war victims in the 
south. 
  His excellency said the government delegation was prepared 
for the forthcoming round of negotiations in Nairobi, and denied 
reports carried by western media that hopes had dimmed over 
Sudan's participation in the forthcoming negotiations, 
especially if the government recaptured Nimule. He said Sudan 
would participate in the negotiations even if all Sudanese 
territory was liberated, because peace is the principal pillar 
upon which stability and development rest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

