<H3> <TI>   Cairo Hosts Talks on Yemen Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cairo Hosts Talks on Yemen Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Musa Comments on Meetings </H4>

<F P=102> NC1906133394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1250 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1906133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 19 Jun (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
said after his meeting with the Yemeni delegation that Lakhdar 
Brahimi, special representative of the UN secretary general, is 
currently making contacts with the parties involved in the 
Yemeni dispute and that these contacts will continue all day. 
  He added that today's meeting was held to exchange views and 
listen to the Yemenis' viewpoint. He pointed out that the 
Egyptian contacts are independent of those being made by Brahimi 
and that they aim to spare Yemen the misfortunes of a continued 
war and help establish a cease-fire and begin a dialogue. 
  Musa said that a north Yemeni delegation will arrive in 
Cairo 
today. 
  Touching on his meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton's 
envoy, he said that it concerned the envoy's special mission in 
Sudan. He added that views were exchanged on the situation 
there. 
  Musa explained that Egypt's stance is clear and that it 
emphasizes the need to preserve Sudan's territorial integrity, 
despite our political differences with that country. However, 
preserving Sudan's territorial integrity is an important matter 
that is part of mutual respect and safeguarding the rights of 
all the Sudanese people, he added. 

</TEXT>

