<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak on African Leaders' Praise for Egypt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mubarak on African Leaders' Praise for Egypt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2006073094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0650 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2006073094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 20 Jun (MENA)--President Husni Mubarak said 
that all the African leaders have praised Egypt's relations with 
all the countries of the world and the international 
organizations that helped to calm the situation in some areas 
and to begin a new era in relations through dialogue and 
understanding. 
  In statements to the weekly newspaper MAYU today, President 
Mubarak added that these African leaders with whom he met in 
Tunis during the recent African summit also praised the decision 
to establish a mechanism to examine conflicts by peaceful means 
and the efforts to reduce African debts. 
  He said that Egypt's status among the African states has 
greatly been enhanced, noting that all the African states with 
whom he met in Tunis thanked Egypt for the large role and 
sincere effort it undertook to solve the problems of the 
continent during Egypt's chairmanship of the OAU in the past 
year. 
  President Mubarak added that all the African leaders have 
felt the genuineness of the efforts Egypt has made to resolve 
the continent's political and economic problems, particularly 
border problems, existing tensions, and internal problems in 
some states. 
  Regarding the Nile water and the danger threatening it as a 
result of the corpses dumped in it from the Rwandan war, 
President Mubarak reassured the people of Egypt that there is no 
danger at all, noting that the Victoria Lake water represents no 
more than 10 percent of the water that reaches Egypt. He said 
that the water is purified and cleaned by natural and 
geographical factors in the course of its long journey. He 
affirmed that Egypt is keen to safeguard its people's health, 
and that this issue is being carefully monitored by the 
pertinent departments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

