<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Denies 'Arafat Appeal To Open Jerusalem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin Denies 'Arafat Appeal To Open Jerusalem </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1706132994 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 17 Jun 94 pp A1, A10 </F>
<F P=103> TA1706132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Aluf Ben, Eytan Rabin, 'Aqiva Eldar, Yerah Tal, </F>
and Sharon Sade] 
  [Excerpt] In his reply to PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat, 
Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin said that Israel has significantly 
eased the closure on the territories but will not lift it 
totally. 'Arafat was given data showing that 45,000 permits for 
work in Israel have already been given to residents of the 
territories and that the entry of women and of youths up to the 
age of 15 is no longer restricted. 
  'Arafat had called on Rabin to ease the plight of the 
residents of the territories, lift the closure and the 
restrictions on work in Israel, open the roadblocks at the 
entrances to Jerusalem, and immediately transfer to the 
Palestinian Authority funds from taxes and customs Israel has 
imposed on the Palestinians. This amount comes to approximately 
6 million shekels, and Israel is holding on to the funds until 
accounts are settled with the Palestinian Authority. 
  Rabin informed 'Arafat that Israel will meet its commitments 
but will not be able to go beyond that. Israel will also not 
lift the roadblocks at the entrances to Jerusalem. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

